  "prompt": "What are the best small classes for freshmen at Western Carolina University?",
  "response": "At Western Carolina University, many students appreciate smaller class sizes for a more personalized learning experience. While specific recommendations can vary based on individual interests and majors, here are some tips and potential class options that students often find beneficial:\n\n1. **Introductory Courses in Major**: Look for foundational courses related to your intended major. These often have smaller sections to facilitate discussion and direct engagement with professors.\n\n2. **General Education Requirements**: Some general education courses, particularly in the humanities or sciences, may offer smaller class sizes. Check with the department for any recommendations.\n\n3. **Freshman Experience or First-Year Seminar**: Many universities offer a seminar specifically designed for freshmen, which usually features smaller class sizes and focuses on skills necessary for academic success.\n\n4. **Courses with Labs**: Classes that include laboratory components (such as biology, chemistry, or environmental science) often have smaller class sizes, allowing for hands-on learning and more interaction.\n\n5. **Special Topics Courses**: These courses can be great for freshmen looking to explore a specific area of interest. They often attract a smaller number of students.\n\n6. **Arts and Humanities Classes**: Courses in art, music, communication, or literature often have smaller class enrollments and encourage discussion and interaction.\n\nTo get the most accurate recommendations, it\u2019s best to consult current students, professors, or academic advisors at Western Carolina University. They can provide insights into which specific classes are currently known for smaller sizes and engaging experiences.",
